      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey i keep getting this \"Connection Reset by Peer\" error on my ec2 instances in us-east-1. it only happens intermittently and usually during peak traffic. i checked the security groups and everything looks theoretically fine but the logs are driving me crazy. \n\nhere is a snippet from cloudwatch:\n2023-10-27T14:22:01Z iid: 4922-X | status: 502 | error: connection reset by peer | client_ip: 192.168.1.45\n\nany idea what might be causing this? specifically if it could be a security group or NACL issue?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "A \"Connection Reset by Peer\" error, especially when it's intermittent and spikes during peak traffic, is rarely just a simple security group or NACL issue, though those are the first things to check. It usually means the other end of the connection—the peer—decided to abruptly drop the connection. It's a classic sign of something being overwhelmed, like a poorly managed resource or a sudden surge of traffic that the receiving end can't handle.\n\nYou should look beyond the basic firewall rules, though, because even the most well-formed security group can be tricked by a massive, poorly behaved client. It's more likely a resource exhaustion issue on the EC2 instance itself, or perhaps a load balancer timing out under stress. I've seen this happen when the instance runs out of ephemeral ports, which is a real bottleneck.\n\nThink about the *peer*. Is it another service, a database, or an external API? If that peer is struggling, it will just yank the plug. It's a common problem, and it's almost always related to capacity, not just permissions.\n\nHere’s what you should check next, though, before you start chasing shadows:\n\n1.  **",
